frican American communities. As an important form of black cultural production, rhythm and blues music helps us to understand black political and cultural desires and longings in light of neo-liberalism's increased codification in America's racial politics and policies since the 1970s. Robert J. Patterson provides a thorough analysis of four artists-Kenneth "Babyface" Edmonds, Adina Howard, Whitney Houston, and Toni Braxton-to examine black cultural longings by demonstrating how our reading of specific moments in their lives, careers, and performances serve as metacommentaries for broader issues in black culture and politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAfrican AmericansxAttitudes. 0aRhythm and blues musicxHistory and criticism. 0aRhythm and blues musicxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aRhythm and blues musicxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  ar&b, rhythm and blues, blues, black culture, african american, inequality, kenneth edmonds, babyface, adina howard, whitney houston, whitney, toni braxton, music, black music, black inequality.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065352640uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9781978803619zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978803619423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781978803619.jpg  a978-3-11-065352-6  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK